          <LI><A=20
          =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/02/nfoworks-harmony-g=
et-ready.asp">nfoWorks:=20
          The Harmony Get-Ready</A>, <EM>Professor von Clueless</EM>,=20
          2008-02-27<BR>specific discussion of the Document =
Interoperability=20
          Initiative and moving along with nfoWorks and the Harmony=20
          Principles<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
          <LI><A=20
          =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/04/nfoworks-what-are-=
those-harmony.asp">nfoWorks:=20
          What Are those Harmony Principles, Again?</A>&nbsp; Professor =
von=20
          Clueless, 2008-04-11<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
          <LI><STRONG><EM><A =
href=3D"http://nfoworks.org/nfoWorks.htm">About=20
          nfoWorks</A></EM></STRONG> and <STRONG><EM></EM></STRONG><A=20
          href=3D"http://nfoworks.org/nfoDiary.htm">nfoWorks Diary</A> =
for=20
          regularly-updated information</LI></UL></UL>
      <H3>1. In Search of Harmony</H3>
      <P>I want an office productivity suite that supports open-standard =

      document formats exclusively.&nbsp; And for any class of document =
(let's=20
      say word-processing, spreadsheet, and presentation to be =
specific), it=20
      only supports open-standard formats in that class in accordance =
with what=20
      I am calling the Harmony Principles:</P>
      <UL>
        <LI><STRONG>Standards Compliant: A<EM>ll</EM> of the =
open-standard=20
        formats in a class are supported without prejudice:</STRONG> =
accept=20
        documents in the supplied format.&nbsp; Produce documents in the =
same or=20
        different standard format as circumstances require.&nbsp; If a=20
        particular community agrees to use a particular format, accept =
and=20
        return that format.&nbsp; If a particular format is required for =

        archiving, preservation, or submission to some authority, submit =
that=20
        format.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Always Harmonious:</STRONG><EM> No</EM> features of =
a=20
        standard format are supported that are not perfectly and =
recognizably=20
        represented in <EM>all</EM> of the formats of the class: =
Everything=20
        created in one standard format is accurately expressible in any=20
        other.&nbsp; Unsupported features encountered in input documents =
are=20
        suppressed in a graceful way; an understandable account is=20
        provided.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Specifically Interoperable:</STRONG> Because =
standards=20
        evolve and so do individual format-supporting software =
implementations,=20
        programs and their users can establish profiles that limit the=20
        harmonious features relied on in particular documents.&nbsp;=20
        Harmony-supporting computer programs will conform their =
available=20
        features to the requirements of such profiles.</LI></UL>
      <P>Given portable, open-source reference implementations of the=20
      essentials, there is opportunity for development of a Harmony for =
Windows,=20
      Harmony for the Mac, Harmony for Linux, Harmony for Google, =
Harmony for=20
      whatever.&nbsp; Other products and implementations of the formats =
that=20
      deliver non-harmonious features could provide optional election of =
Harmony=20
      Principles, particularly whenever an interoperability profile is=20
      encountered.&nbsp; </P>
      <P>A Harmony suite could easily live alongside configurations of =
people's=20
      favorite broader-function office suite, just like Microsoft Works =
and=20
      similar mini-suites can be found by default on many computers that =
have=20
      additional productivity software.&nbsp; Whether the components =
could be=20
      operated usefully together is an opportunity for innovation beyond =
the=20
      basic parameters of the Harmony Principles.</P>
      <H3>2. <EM>You</EM> Have Questions?&nbsp; <EM>I</EM> Have =
Questions!</H3>
      <UL>
        <LI><STRONG>Q:</STRONG> Won't the interoperability intersection =
be so=20
        small that no one would limit themselves to it?<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <BR><STRONG>A:</STRONG> Perhaps.&nbsp; I have no idea.&nbsp; =
Let's find=20
        out.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Q:</STRONG> Won't the performance of Harmony be =
worse than=20
        the optimization that is possible by dealing well with a single=20
        open-standard document format?<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; =
<BR><STRONG>A:</STRONG>=20
        In principle, probably.&nbsp; In practice I expect a Harmony =
reference=20
        implementation to be noticeably less capable.&nbsp; Optimization =
comes=20
        after figuring out how to do it at all and takes a substantial=20
        investment that only serious competitors might=20
        undertake.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Q:</STRONG> How Is "accurately expressible"=20
        determined?<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR><STRONG>A:</STRONG> I don't =
know.&nbsp;=20
        I'm thinking one measure would be achievement of the same =
presentation=20
        in some neutral medium, say some canonical PDF rendition that it =
is easy=20
        to compare against.&nbsp; Another is roundtrip fidelity between=20
        different formats and back, in terms of what people see and what =
they=20
        can manipulate.&nbsp; These strike me as variants on acceptance =
tests=20
        that are already needed for demonstrating conformance to a =
single=20
        open-standard format.&nbsp; It will take experimentation to find =

        adequate measures.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Q:</STRONG> You seem to put a lot of stock in =
profiles for=20
        constraining dependence on features.&nbsp; Is this just more =
standards=20
        work?<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; <BR><STRONG>A:</STRONG> I don't =
know.&nbsp; I=20
        don't think any of the current open-standard formats provide for =

        constraint on the document architecture for some =
externally-defined,=20
        utilitarian purpose.&nbsp; I don't think there is enough =
understanding=20
        about how this can be expressed across different (or the same) =
formats=20
        to consider whether there should be any standard for it.&nbsp; =
Let's=20
        find out how to do it at all first.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Q:</STRONG> What makes you think that major=20
        office-productivity software producers would support the Harmony =

        Principles?<BR>&nbsp; <BR><STRONG>A:</STRONG> I have no =
idea.&nbsp; I=20
        think it depends on first determining what is feasible under =
easy=20
        conditions, then see what is valuable to users of major =
more-complex and=20
        more-sophisticated software products.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Q:</STRONG> Is there anything you're sure of =
concerning the=20
        practical achievability of Harmony?<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <BR><STRONG>A:</STRONG> I'm sure I don't know.&nbsp; Oh, yes, =
and I am=20
        sure that it is bigger and more difficult than I can get my head =
around,=20
        especially operating alone in my private echo chamber.</LI></UL>
      <H3>3. Well Then, Let's Start Getting Started Shall We?</H3>
      <P>Something I am more confident of as a starting point is a suite =
of=20
      exploratory tools and exercises that I call=20
      <STRONG><EM>nfoWorks</EM></STRONG>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That =
development can=20
      proceed along the following lines:</P>
      <UL>
        <LI><STRONG>Deliver Concrete Artifacts.</STRONG>&nbsp; Don't =
produce=20
        anything without working software and repeatable demonstrations =
and=20
        tests.&nbsp; Do this early and often, no matter how crude.&nbsp; =

        <BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Operate Entirely in Public.</STRONG>&nbsp; Use =
SourceForge,=20
        Wikis, etc.&nbsp; Provide open-source software.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Start Very, Very Small.</STRONG>&nbsp; Find the =
minimal=20
        cases that work for demonstrating and exercising open-standard =
document=20
        formats and isolating the interoperability intersections.&nbsp; =
Build=20
        out incrementally and iteratively.&nbsp; Always have something =
that=20
        works.<BR>&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Make Tools and Instruments</STRONG>.&nbsp; Build =
filters and=20
        conformance tests as a way to accept the proper formats, verify =
outputs,=20
        and check inter-translation of identified harmonious =
features.<BR>&nbsp;=20

        <LI><STRONG>Develop Measurable Harmony =
Principles</STRONG>.&nbsp; Learn=20
        by doing and identify what it is that must be preserved across=20
        implementations/formats and how to tell that it =
is.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>Devise Portable Approaches.</STRONG>&nbsp; Don't get =
stuck=20
        on a single platform.&nbsp; Design in portability for broad=20
        reuse.<BR>&nbsp;=20
        <LI><STRONG>GUI Applications and User Experience Come Last, if=20
        Ever.</STRONG>&nbsp; So we are not talking about something, at =
this=20
        point, where end-user operability dominates.&nbsp; Really.&nbsp; =
We need=20
        to understand this problem at the nuts-and-bolts =
format-manipulation=20
        level.&nbsp; After there is a clear path, step up to the very =
real=20
        difficulties of fitting into the ways that people actually =
operate=20
        without getting in their way [<A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2008/02/odf-ooxml-nfoworks=
-for-harmony.asp#2">2</A>].</LI></UL>
      <H3>4. Hmm, Now What?</H3>
      <P>I think I need to get my arms around the "start very, very =
small part"=20
      without losing site of the overall objective.&nbsp; That may take =
some=20
      relaxed "get ready to get started" work.&nbsp; </P>
      <P>I probably don't need to know anything about changes to DIS =
29500=20
      (OOXML) as the result of the up-coming Ballot Resolution Meeting, =
but I=20
      think I will use that time and some of the aftermath to start =
providing=20
      details that are more substantial than this high-level =
thinking-it-over:=20
      Something others can get there teeth into.&nbsp; This is not the =
kind of=20
      open-source project I can even think of doing single-handedly, so =
I need=20
      to think about how others can be engaged too.</P>
      <P>What do you think?</P>
      <HR>
      <SMALL>
      <P>I've been mulling over some sort of ODF-OOXML common=20
      document-processing approach for some time.&nbsp; I'm using my =
preparation=20
      for ODC2008 attendance as a stimulant to putting something on the=20
      table.&nbsp; </P>
      <DL>
        <DT>[<A name=3D1>1</A>] Dennis E. Hamilton: <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2007/03/why-not-suitabilit=
y-of-rtf-for-open.asp">Why=20
        Not .rtfx?</A>&nbsp; <EM>Professor von Clueless in the Blunder =
Dome</EM>=20
        (web log), 2007-03-26.=20
        <DD>This came out of my tracking of the Massachusetts =
Information=20
        Technology Division list of qualified document formats under =
versions of=20
        their Enterprise Technical Reference Model.&nbsp; I have more to =
say=20
        about opportunities to use Open Packaging Conventions as a =
powerful=20
        carrier for interchange of document-based artifacts.&nbsp; This =
kind of=20
        project can also spin off as early application of=20
        <STRONG><EM>nfoWorks</EM></STRONG> fixtures, or <EM>vice=20
        versa</EM>.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
        <DT>[<A name=3D2>2</A>] Dennis E. Hamilton: <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/02/ooxml-odf-harmonization-hope-chest=
.asp">OOXML-ODF:=20
        The Harmonization Hope Chest</A>.&nbsp; <EM>Orcmid's Lair</EM> =
(web=20
        log), 2008-02-06 (2008-02-07 updates).=20
        <DD>My ponderings over this post also improved my thinking about =

        <STRONG><EM>nfoWorks</EM></STRONG> (including choice of=20
        name).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </DD></DL>
